## 1. LU Factorisation

Just as Gramâ€“Schmidt can be reinterpreted as a reduced QR factorisation,
Gaussian elimination  can be interpreted as an LU factorisation. Write a matrix
$A âˆˆ â„‚^{n Ã— n}$ as follows:
$$
A =  \begin{bmatrix} Î±_1 & ğ°_1^âŠ¤ \\ ğ¯_1 & A_2 \end{bmatrix}
$$
where $Î±_1 = a_{11}$, $ğ¯_1 = A[2:n, 1]$ and $ğ°_1 = A[1, 2:n]$. Gaussian elimination consists of taking the first row, dividing by
$Î±$ and subtracting from all other rows. That is equivalent to multiplying by a lower triangular matrix:
$$
\begin{bmatrix}
1 \\
-ğ¯_1/Î±_1 & I \end{bmatrix} A = \begin{bmatrix} Î±_1 & ğ°_1^âŠ¤ \\  & K -ğ¯_1ğ°_1^âŠ¤ /Î±_1 \end{bmatrix}
$$
where $A_2 := K -ğ¯_1 ğ°_1^âŠ¤/Î±_1$  happens to be a rank-1 perturbation of $K$. 
Assume $A_2 = L_2 U_2$.
We can write this another way:
$$
A = \underbrace{\begin{bmatrix}
1 \\
ğ¯_1/Î±_1 & I \end{bmatrix}}_{L_1}  \begin{bmatrix} Î±_1 & ğ°_1^âŠ¤ \\  & A_2 \end{bmatrix}
= \underbrace{L_1 \begin{bmatrix}
1 \\
 & L_2 \end{bmatrix}}_{L}  \underbrace{\begin{bmatrix} Î±_1 & ğ°_1^âŠ¤ \\  & U_2 \end{bmatrix}}_{U}
$$
Note we can multiply through to find
$$
L = \begin{bmatrix}
1 \\
ğ¯_1/Î±_1 & L_2 \end{bmatrix}
$$

This procedure implies an algorithm:

**Algorithm 1 (LU)** Let $A_1 := A$. For $k = 1, â€¦, n-1$ define
$$
\begin{align*}
Î±_k &:= A_k[1,1] \\
ğ¯_k &:= A_k[2:n-k+1,1] \\
ğ°_k &:= A_k[1, 2:n-k+1] \\
A_{k+1} &:= A_k[2:n-k+1,2:n-k+1]-ğ¯_k ğ°_k^âŠ¤/Î±_k,
\end{align*}
$$
and $Î±_n := A_n[1,1]$. 
Then for $â„“_{kj} := ğ¯_j[k-j]/Î±_j$ and $u_{kj} = ğ°_k[j-k]$ we have
$$
A = \underbrace{\begin{bmatrix}1 \\ â„“_{21} & 1 \\
                â„“_{31} & â„“_{32} & 1 \\
                â‹® &  â‹® & â‹± & â‹± \\
                â„“_{n1} & â„“_{n2} & â‹¯ & â„“_{n,n-1} & 1
                \end{bmatrix}}_L \underbrace{\begin{bmatrix} Î±_1 &u_{12} & u_{13} & â‹¯ & u_{1n} \\
                                          & Î±_2 & u_{23} & â‹¯ & u_{2n} \\
                                        && â‹± & â‹± & â‹® \\
                                        &&& Î±_{n-1} & u_{n-1,n} \\
                                        &&&& Î±_n\end{bmatrix}}_U
$$





