## 2. PLU Factorisation

We learned in first year linear algebra that if a diagonal entry is zero
whem doing Gaussian elimnation one has to _row pivot_. For stability, 
in implementation one _always_ pivots: swap the largest in magnitude entry for the entry on the diagonal.
We will see this is equivalent to a PLU decomposition:


**Theorem 1 (PLU)** A matrix $A âˆˆ â„‚^{n Ã— n}$ is invertible if and only if it has a PLU decomposition:
$$
A = P^âŠ¤ L U
$$
where the diagonal of $L$ are all equal to 1 and the diagonal of $U$ are all non-zero.

**Proof**

If we have a PLU decomposition of this form then $L$ and $U$ are invertible and hence the inverse is simply $A^{-1} = U^{-1} L^{-1} P$. 

We will prove the other direction by induction.
If $A âˆˆ â„‚^{1 Ã— 1}$ we trivially have an LU decomposition $A = [1] * [a_{11}]$ as all matrices are triangular.
As $A$ is invertible not all entries in the first column are zero. Therefore there exists a permutation
$P_1$ so that $Î± := (P_1 A)[1,1] â‰ Â 0$. Hence we write
$$
P_1 A = \begin{bmatrix} Î± & ğ°^âŠ¤ \\
                        ğ¯ & A_2
                        \end{bmatrix} = \underbrace{\begin{bmatrix}
1 \\
ğ¯/Î± & I \end{bmatrix}}_{L_1}  \begin{bmatrix} Î± & ğ°^âŠ¤ \\  & A_2 \end{bmatrix}
$$
We know $A_2$ is invertible: if $A_2^âŠ¤ ğœ  = ğŸ$ then for $ğ := P_1^âŠ¤ L_1^{-âŠ¤} [0; ğœ]$ we have
$$
\begin{align*}
ğ^âŠ¤ A =  [0\ ğœ^âŠ¤] L_1^{-1} P_1 P_1^âŠ¤ L_1  \begin{bmatrix} Î± & ğ°^âŠ¤ \\  & A_2 \end{bmatrix}
= [0\ ğœ^âŠ¤] \begin{bmatrix} Î± & ğ°^âŠ¤ \\  & A_2 \end{bmatrix} = [0\ ğœ^âŠ¤\ A_2] = ğŸ^âŠ¤.
\end{align*}
$$
Thus by induction $A_2 = P_2^âŠ¤ L_2 U_2$. Thus we have:
$$
\begin{align*}
\begin{bmatrix} 1 \\
            & P_2 \end{bmatrix} P_1 A &= \begin{bmatrix} 1 \\
            & P_2 \end{bmatrix}  \begin{bmatrix} Î± & ğ°^âŠ¤ \\
                        ğ¯ & A_2
                        \end{bmatrix}  =
            \begin{bmatrix} 1 \\ & P_2 \end{bmatrix} L_1  \begin{bmatrix} Î± & ğ°^âŠ¤ \\  & P_2^âŠ¤ L_2 U_2 \end{bmatrix} \\
            &= \begin{bmatrix}
1 \\
P_2 ğ¯/Î± & P_2 \end{bmatrix} \begin{bmatrix} 1 &  \\  &  P_2^âŠ¤ L_2 \end{bmatrix}  \begin{bmatrix} Î± & ğ°^âŠ¤ \\  &  U_2 \end{bmatrix} \\
&= \underbrace{\begin{bmatrix}
1 \\
P_2 ğ¯/Î± & L_2 \end{bmatrix}}_L \underbrace{\begin{bmatrix} Î± & ğ°^âŠ¤ \\  &  U_2 \end{bmatrix}}_U. \\
\end{align*}
$$

âˆ

In the above we neglected to state which permutation is used as for the proof of existence it is immaterial. For _stability_ however, 
we choose one that puts the largest entry: let $Ïƒ_{\rm max} : â„^n â†’ S_n$ be the permutation that swaps the first row with the row
of $ğš$ whose absolute value is maximised.
In cycle notation we then have:
$$
Ïƒ_{\rm max}(ğš) = (1, {\rm indmax} |ğš|)
$$
where ${\rm indmax}$ gives the index of the entry of a vector which is its maximum.
This inductive proof encodes an  algorithm:

**Algorithm 2 (PLU)** Let $A_1 := A$. For $k = 1, â€¦, n-1$ define
$$
\begin{align*}
Ïƒ_k &:= Ïƒ_{\rm max}(A_k[1:n-k+1,1]) \\
P_k &:= P_{Ïƒ_k} \\
AÌƒ_k & := P_k A_k \\
Î±_k &:= AÌƒ_k[1,1] \\
ğ¯_k &:= AÌƒ_k[2:n-k+1,1] \\
ğ°_k &:= AÌƒ_k[1, 2:n-k+1] \\
A_{k+1} &:= AÌƒ_k[2:n-k+1,2:n-k+1]-ğ¯_k ğ°_k^âŠ¤/Î±_k,
\end{align*}
$$
and finally $Î±_n := A_n[1,1]$. 
Then for $â„“_{kj} := ğ¯_j[k-j]/Î±_j$, $u_{kj} = ğ°_k[j-k]$, and
$$
PÌƒ_k := \begin{bmatrix} I_{k-1} \\ & P_k \end{bmatrix}
$$
 we have
$$
\underbrace{PÌƒ_{Ïƒ_{n-1}} â‹¯ PÌƒ_{Ïƒ_1}}_P A = \underbrace{\begin{bmatrix}1 \\ â„“_{21} & 1 \\
                â„“_{31} & â„“_{32} & 1 \\
                â‹® &  â‹® & â‹± & â‹± \\
                â„“_{n1} & â„“_{n2} & â‹¯ & â„“_{n,n-1} & 1
                \end{bmatrix}}_L \underbrace{\begin{bmatrix} Î±_1 &u_{12} & u_{13} & â‹¯ & u_{1n} \\
                                          & Î±_2 & u_{23} & â‹¯ & u_{2n} \\
                                        && â‹± & â‹± & â‹® \\
                                        &&& Î±_{n-1} & u_{n-1,n} \\
                                        &&&& Î±_n\end{bmatrix}}_U
$$


**Example 3**

Again we consider the matrix
$$
